# Design system & UX (TFD Tracker)

## North star
- **Discovery first:** persistent navigation, categorized tabs, filters that stay useful across patches — not decorative empty chrome.
- **Data-dense & scannable:** build cards and lists should surface *target, type, key modules, reactor, sets* at a glance (Overframe-style density).
- **Game-native feel:** tier colors and bordered “chip” controls should echo the in-game module UI without copying copyrighted assets.

## Tier tokens (map to Nexon `module_tier_id` / in-game labels)
Use these **semantic names** in new CSS and components; align with existing classes in `globals.css`:

| Token | Nexon tier | Role | Existing UI hooks (examples) |
|-------|------------|------|------------------------------|
| **tier1** | Tier1 / Normal | baseline | `.tier-normal`, `.tier-common`, `.tier-norm` |
| **tier2** | Tier2 / Rare | mid | `.tier-rare`, `.rarity-chip-rare` |
| **tier3** | Tier3 / Ultimate | high | `.tier-ultimate`, `.rarity-chip-ultimate` |
| **tier4** | Tier4 / Transcendent | top | `.tier-transcendent`, Transcendent borders in builder |

Prefer **CSS variables** on `:root` for new work (e.g. `--tier-t4`, `--tier-t3`) and reference them from tier classes — avoid hardcoding one-off hex codes for tier colors in new components.

## Module / “chipset” aesthetic
- **Borders + compact metadata:** capacity number, socket pill, tier strip — same information hierarchy as the build planner library cards.
- **Chips:** `filter-chip`, skill chips, socket labels — rounded rects, subtle border, readable at small sizes.

## Build calculator (math engine)
- **Capacity, sockets, and Nexon JSON** are authoritative — see `tfd-nexon-data.mdc` and `src/lib/tfd-modules.ts`.
- New mechanics (catalysts, auto-socket rules, etc.) belong in **typed lib code** with tests or clear comments; do not duplicate magic numbers in components.

## What not to do
- Don’t invent tier colors or module stats — use Nexon Open API + library.
- Don’t replace scannable lists with hero-only landing art on functional pages.
- Don’t add new global styles without checking `globals.css` for duplicates (see HANDOFF history).

